A One-Sided Minimax Theorem. In the way that Theorem 7.1 generalized the
finite minimax theorem by allowing Y to be an arbitrary set, Theorem 7.2 may be generalized
to allow Y to be arbitrary, provided we keep the compactness condition on X.
The continuity condition may be weakened to assuming only that A(x, y) is a continuous
function of x for every y ‚àà Y . And even this can be weakened to assuming that A(x, y) is
only upper semi-continuous in x for every y ‚àà Y .
II ‚Äì 80
A function f(x) defined on X is upper semi-continuous at a point x0 ‚àà X, if for any
sequence x1, x2,... of points in X such that limn‚Üí‚àû xn = x0, we have limn‚Üí‚àû f(xn) ‚â§
f(x0). It is upper semi-continuous (usc) on X if it is upper semicontinuous at every point
of X. A function f(x) is lower semi-continuous (lsc) if the above inequality is changed to
limn‚Üí‚àû f(xn) ‚â• f(x0), or equivalently, if the function, ‚àíf(x), is upper semi-continuous.
As an example, the function
f(x) =  0 if x < 0
a if x = 0
1 if x > 0
is usc if a ‚â• 1 and lsc if a ‚â§ 0. It is neither usc nor lsc if 0 <a< 1.
Theorem 7.3. If X is a compact subset of Euclidean space, and if A(x, y) is an upper
semi-continuous function of x ‚àà X for all y ‚àà Y and if A is bounded below (or if Y ‚àó is the
set of finite mixtures), then the game has a value, Player I has an optimal strategy in X‚àó,
and for every  > 0 Player II has an -optimal strategy giving weight to a finite number of
points.
Similarly from Player II‚Äôs viewpoint, if Y is a compact subset of Euclidean space, and
if A(x, y) is a lower semi-continuous function of y ‚àà Y for all x ‚àà X and if A is bounded
above (or if X‚àó is the set of finite mixtures), then the game has a value and Player II has
an optimal strategy in Y ‚àó.
Example 2. Player I chooses a number in [0,1] and Player II tries to guess what it
is. Player I wins 1 if Player II‚Äôs guess is off by at least 1/3; otherwise, there is no payoff.
Thus, X = Y = [0, 1], and A(x, y) =  1 if |x ‚àí y| ‚â• 1/3
0 if |x ‚àí y| < 1/3. Although the payoff
function is not continuous, it is upper semi-continuous in x for every y ‚àà Y . Thus the
game has a value and Player I has an optimal mixed strategy.
If we change the payoff so that Player I wins 1 if Player II‚Äôs guess is off by more than
1/3, then A(x, y) =  1 if |x ‚àí y| > 1/3
0 if |x ‚àí y| ‚â§ 1/3. This is no longer upper semi-continuous in x
for fixed y; instead it is lower semi-continuous in y for each x ‚àà X. This time, the game
has a value and Player II has an optimal mixed strategy.
7.3 Concave Games and Convex Games. If in Theorem 7.2, we add the assumption
that the payoff function A(x, y) is concave in x for all y or convex in y for all x, then
we can conclude that one of the players has an optimal pure strategy, which is usually easy
to find. Here is a one-sided version that complements Theorem 7.3. A good reference for
these ideas is the book of Karlin (1959), vol. 2.
Theorem 7.4. Let (X, Y, A) be a game with Y arbitrary, X a compact, convex subset of
Rm, and A(x, y) bounded below. If A(x, y) is a concave function of x ‚àà X for all y ‚àà Y ,
then the game has a value and Player I has an optimal pure strategy. Moreover, Player II
has an -optimal strategy that is a mixture of at most m + 1 pure strategies.
II ‚Äì 81
The dual statement for convex functions is: If Y is compact and convex in Rn, and
if A is bounded above and is convex in y ‚àà Y for all x ‚àà X, then the game has a value,
Player II has an optimal pure strategy and Player I has -optimal strategies giving weight
to at most n + 1 points..
These games may be solved by a method similar to Method 1 of Section 7.1. Let‚Äôs
see how to find the optimal strategy of Player II in the convex functio case. Let g(y) =
supx A(x, y) be the upper envelope. Then g(y) is finite since A is bounded above. It is also
convex since the supremum of any set of convex functions is convex. Then since convex
functions defined on a compact set attain their maximum, there exists a point y‚àó at which
g(y) takes on its maximum value, so that
A(x, y‚àó) ‚â§ max x A(x, y‚àó) = g(y‚àó) for all x ‚àà X.
Any such point is an optimal pure strategy for Player II. By choosing y‚àó, Player II will
lose no more than g(y‚àó) no matter what Player I does. Player I‚Äôs optimal strategy is
more complex to describe in general; it gives weight only to points that play a role in the
upper envelope at the point y‚àó. These are points x such that A(x, y) is tangent (or nearly
tangent if only -optimal strategies exist) to the surface g(y) at y‚àó. It is best to consider
examples.
Example 1. Estimation. Player I chooses a point x ‚àà X = [0, 1], and Player II
tries to choose a point y ‚àà Y = [0, 1] close to x. Player II loses the square of the distance
from x to y: A(x, y)=(x ‚àí y)2. This is a convex function of y ‚àà [0, 1] for all x ‚àà X.
For any x, A(x, y) is bounded above by either A(0, y) or A(1, y) so the upper envelope
is g(y) = max{A(0, y), A(1, y)} = max{y2,(1 ‚àí y)2}. This is minimized at y‚àó = 1/2. If
Player II uses y‚àó, she is guaranteed to lose no more than g(y‚àó)=1/4.
Since x = 0 and x = 1 are the only two pure strategies influencing the upper envelope,
and since y2 and (1‚àíy)2 have slopes at y‚àó that are equal in absolute value but opposite in
sign, Player I should mix 0 and 1 with equal probability. This mixed strategy has convex
payoff (1/2)(A(0, y) + A(1, y)) with slope zero at y‚àó. Player I is guaranteed winning at
least 1/4, so v = 1/4 is the value of the game. The pure strategy y‚àó is optimal for Player
II and the mixed strategy, 0 with probability 1/2 and 1 with probability 1/2, is optimal for
Player I. In this example, n = 1, and Player I‚Äôs optimal strategy mixes 2 = n + 1 points.
Theorem 7.4 may also be stated with the roles of the players reversed. If Y is arbitrary,
and if X is a compact subset of Rm and if A(x, y) is bounded below and concave in x ‚àà X
for all y ‚àà Y , then Player I has an optimal pure strategy, and Player II has an -optimal
strategy mixing at most m +1 pure strategies. It may also happen that A(x, y) is concave
in x for all y, and convex in y for all x. In that case, both players have optimal pure
strategies as in the following example.
Example 2. A Convex-Concave Game. Suppose X = Y = [0, 1], and A(x, y) =
‚àí2x2 +4xy+y2 ‚àí2x‚àí3y+1. The payoff is convex in y for all x and concave in x for all y.
Therefore, both players have pure optimal strategies, say x0 and y0. If Player II uses y0,
